Next week, the Social Affairs Committee of the Parliament will discuss the law on providing psychiatric care.
Psychiatrists are the only medical specialists for whom minors under the age of eighteen need parental consent to access their services.
Experts involved in the committee's work have repeatedly pointed out the need to change the law.
Ave H asked why the amendment has been stuck in Parliament.
The gap in the law does not allow minors under the age of eighteen to seek psychiatric care without parental consent.
Although the ruling elite has repeatedly affirmed the need to change the law, young people continue to be left without assistance every month.
Young people should always have the opportunity to seek help for themselves, regardless of what their family members think about it, meaning that the suspicion of seeking help for mental health problems from all families has not disappeared.
The current law is largely based on the assumption that all children have supportive parents, a functioning family who can support their child and make decisions on their behalf. Unfortunately, in my work experience, I see that this situation is often different, as not all parents are able or willing to deal with their child's problems, whether they lack the necessary skills, need help themselves, or even cause their child's problems.
The Social Affairs Committee of the Parliament has discussed the issue six times. Various aspects of the problem have been explained by professionals and representatives of thirty-six organizations, who have also signed a joint appeal justifying the importance of amending the law.
A year and a half has passed since the Chancellor of Justice drew the state's attention to the fact that this small amendment to the law would be fair and necessary for young people.
Today, we are in a situation where the Social Affairs Committee of the Parliament has been dealing with this issue for almost a year, and even the Ministry of Education, Ministry of Justice, Ministry of Social Affairs, as well as the Prime Minister and Minister of Social Affairs have expressed their support for this small amendment. Yet, we are still processing it and cannot reach a decision.
What initially seemed like a small and simple amendment to the law has turned into a fundamental opposition. Urmas Espenberg, a member of the Social Affairs Committee from the EKRE party, says that theoretically, they agree that young people should be able to see a psychiatrist without their parents' permission in exceptional cases. However, in practice, no agreement can be reached. According to Espenberg, there are two exceptional cases where a young person could see a psychiatrist without their parents' consent - the absence of a legal guardian or domestic violence.
I certainly do not agree that everyone will start going to psychiatrists for their own desires, so that every random child will go to a psychologist for counseling and then the psychologist will decide what to do next.
What do opponents of the law amendments fear? Do they not trust young people or do they not trust professionals, namely psychiatrists?
Espenberg highlights the need to work with families, fear that young people will be prescribed too strong medications, but also the fear that mental health issues will become a trend or that young people will sell prescribed medications on the black market.
Young people are prone to trying all sorts of things and when the talk starts that everyone can now go, then the talk about antidepressants starts, then maybe they will start selling it to each other.
The psychiatrist dispels the fears of opponents of the law changes, as it is the doctor's task and competence to assess the patient's condition and act accordingly.
It is always the doctor's wisdom to see through these situations, to see what motives are actually behind it and how the use of medication is, meaning that there are rules in place that, if followed, will prevent most of these problems.
According to both specialized doctors and youth workers, the problem is serious and requires action.
I approached thirteen youth workers from four different institutions and one third of them have actually encountered situations where a child needs psychiatric help, but due to the parent's response, it has not been found.
I also asked for their stories, which are sometimes frightening, two of them have reached attempted suicide, fortunately unsuccessful, one of them is an ongoing process where the child is afraid to contact their parents, as their parents are strongly convinced that mental health issues are something only for the insane or the highly spiritual.
Urmas Espenberg suggests a solution that a referral or permission to a psychiatrist could be issued by another adult who works with young people.
In practice, this means that we have all kinds of networks, there is the network for youth and child protection, then there is the police, where certain cases are registered, they can make a referral there, then there are school psychologists who can be turned to, there are many possibilities and there are many psychologists in Estonia and they are all relatively underutilized, so we should think about how to solve these things, not blame each other.
Each intermediate stage, however, increases bureaucracy and requires additional resources, currently the problem is to fulfill existing requirements, only thirty-one percent of Estonian schools have a psychologist, which means that more than half of the schools have to manage without a psychologist.
Where they are, they are very capable, and where they are not, there is a great shortage of them.
What happens when a person does not receive help at the right time?
In the case of mental disorders, one of the most common being depression, there is a high risk that it will become chronic, but before that, it will ruin your quality of life, meaning that a young person cannot study, cannot communicate, cannot fulfill themselves in life, and they disrupt daily life, for example, sitting at home in front of the computer, not eating sausage anymore, but lying down there.
The number of people infected with Covid-19 exceeded two hundred on several days this week, and Minister of Social Affairs Tanel Kiik said on Friday that due to the spread of Covid-19, Estonia is heading towards a health crisis.
Hanneli Rudi investigated how the virus is currently spreading.
Two hundred and eight, one hundred and thirty-one, two hundred and forty-one, these are not winning points in some dart game, but rather the numbers of people infected with Covid-19 this week, sad records in a way.
However, in mid-October, Estonia stood out in Europe with exceptionally low infection rates.
Now, in Tallinn and Harju County, the source of infection can no longer be determined in every other case, meaning that the disease has started to spread covertly.
Was it really predictable, but well, Covid-19 is such that it tends to not always grow evenly, but rather in sudden outbreaks, but does this mean that things got out of hand, well, I wouldn't say that right now, the growth rate is certainly the highest in the east and we definitely cannot handle it calmly until spring.
According to Covid-19 modeler Mario Kadastik, such a rapid increase in infections is expected, as the infection rate R, which shows how many people one infected person passes the virus on to, has been between 1.2 and 1.4 in the past couple of weeks.
By Saturday, this had risen to one point five, which means that two patients transmitted the infection to three others, even if the infection rate does not increase, it would be a serious threat to the Estonian healthcare system, as hospitals would be filled with Covid patients by the end of the year.
Although there has been a lot of talk about whether there are enough ventilators for everyone with Covid-19, Kadastik says that the entire healthcare system will actually be in a serious crisis.
And if this system now completely gets out of hand, as it has in some places in the world where hospitals are only filled with Covid patients, then the problem arises that we can no longer treat other things that are very treatable.
Covid wards also require significantly more staff and therefore it is not possible to continuously create more beds there. According to Kadastik, it would be wise to make an effort to get the situation under control before the critical limit is reached. Based on the current numbers, he believes it is more accurate to talk about the beginning phase of a large wave, rather than the spread of the disease in waves.
It will continue with small fluctuations until the Health Board can reach most of the contacts.
Well, we have been on the edge for a long time and our very capable inspectors from the Northern Regional Department are doing their best. Of course, the use of a speech robot has been very helpful.
The speech robot does give instructions to close contacts, but experience has shown that this is not enough, as people often do not understand the robot's message. Therefore, the coronavirus detectives working in Tallinn have received help from about ten people who make calls to people. Assistance has also come from coronavirus detectives in other regions.
Could there be a situation where you simply give up on finding close contacts or is this scenario completely ruled out?
This scenario is completely possible if we cannot keep the infection under control, right? And it is very important right now that we all behave correctly, because everything is in our hands.
If the strength of the coronavirus detectives weakens, Kadastik believes that there will be no escape from general restrictions.
In any case of exponential growth, the longer it lasts, the harder it is to eliminate the situation, so the sooner we get on top of it, the easier it will be to get rid of it.
Kadastik recommends avoiding face-to-face communication as much as possible, keeping a distance from strangers, and if that is not possible, then using a mask.
According to scientists, it is important to remember that the result of today's actions or restrictions will only affect the Covid-19 statistics in two to four weeks.
The science council advising the government has already presented their recommendations for restrictions.
Instead of reinstating the two plus two rule, they simply recommended a two-meter distance requirement.
This, or, well, if the nightlife is closed, we did recommend that, or, the minimum reduction, but no one is currently prohibited from wearing a mask in closed spaces, so please, people, wear a mask, does J체ri Ratas really have to tell you that?
Let's now see how many of us can be affected by one person's infection.
The Health Board described to us a real virus outbreak, where there were an exceptionally high number of close contacts.
Five hundred people were put in isolation, many of whom had to interrupt their work for two weeks.
The case revolves around a father, as the virus traveled to Estonia with the father of the family from abroad.
The returning father infected his wife, son, son's partner, two daughters, and daughter's child.
The infected mother worked in a care facility, where she came into contact with ninety-five people.
Her close contacts were tested twice, none of them fell ill.
One colleague of the son, who worked in a large collective, fell ill and three hundred and sixty-five close contacts were put under surveillance, none of whom fell ill.
This infected colleague brought the infection to their home and five people in their family became infected.
The son's partner worked in a restaurant, which was closed and fourteen contacts were sent to isolation, luckily no one fell ill.
The daughter, who attends school, had twenty-one close contacts, who were all sent to home isolation, none of them fell ill.
The granddaughter's kindergarten was closed and fourteen close contacts were under surveillance, none of them fell ill.
In addition, eighteen family acquaintances were in isolation, none of whom fell ill, and as a result of this outbreak, thirteen people became infected and five hundred and twenty-seven people were in two-week isolation and under the supervision of the Health Board.
